  "rehber1Baslik": "1. What Does İTOGENA Do?",
  "rehber1Kutu": "İTOGENA reads simple field data together with time, process, lineage, performance and apiary calibration to produce actionable colony decisions. The goal is not merely record-keeping; it is to clearly show the beekeeper what to do, why, and when.",
  "rehber1M1": "The system works on a trigger → process → suggestion → field action → new inspection → closure logic.",
  "rehber1M2": "Colony class is derived from a single biological source: if functional production frames are 0–3 it is weak, 4–7 is development, 8–9 is production, and 10 or above is harvest class.",
  "rehber1M3": "It does not ask for additional confirmation for each process; it tries to understand the outcome from the next inspection data.",
  "rehber1M4": "The colony detail screen opens quickly; heavy analyses are loaded in the background.",
  "rehber1M5": "The system reads physical frames and functional production capacity separately. Rapid expansion, foundation frame loading, or post-harvest volume changes are not automatically treated as a strong colony.",
  "rehber1M6": "The colony detail general status screen shows four main headings: Process, Biology, Management and Genetics.",
  "rehber1M7": "The management card standardises feeding, super, space, varroa, winter and post-harvest care decisions in the same management list.",
  "rehber1M8": "When inspection, colony or apiary data changes, all caches are cleared together; the risk of an old decision remaining on screen is reduced.",

  "rehber2Baslik": "2. Free and PRO",
  "rehber2Kutu": "You can use ITOGENA for free for inspection records and basic colony tracking. The free tier supports up to 10 colonies and 1 apiary. Deep analysis, risk monitoring, harvest estimation, reporting, and unlimited colonies/apiaries are PRO features.",

  "rehber3Baslik": "3. What Does the System Read from Frames?",
  "rehber3M1": "Frame count is the primary field indicator of colony strength; it is not a definitive decision on its own.",
  "rehber3M2": "The last frame reflects current live strength, the maximum frame indicates in-season capacity, and honey frames reflect productivity during the production period.",
  "rehber3M3": "In winter, frame strength matters for resilience; honey frames are not read as winter performance.",
  "rehber3M4": "The system reads frame count not just as a number but as estimated biological capacity: bee population, cell capacity, brood/stock area, queen zone and harvest potential are all derived from this data.",
  "rehber3M5": "These values are not precise measurements; climate, flora, bee breed, season and management differences can change the outcome.",
  "rehber3M6": "Langstroth is the default reference. If Dadant is selected, the same biological layout is maintained but frame capacity is calculated with a higher coefficient.",
  "rehber3M7": "If a feeder is present, the lower brood box is assumed to be 9 frames; without a feeder, 10 frames. Frames above this limit are interpreted as super/honey space.",

  "rehber3bBaslik": "3B. Functional Frames and Volume Activation",
  "rehber3bM1": "İTOGENA reads physical frames and functional frames separately. The number of frames in the hive represents physical volume, while the space the colony can actually use represents functional biological capacity.",
  "rehber3bM2": "A newly added frame is not immediately counted as full capacity. The system calculates an activation period based on whether it is a foundation or drawn comb, the number of days elapsed, brood layout, colony strength and the honey flow window.",
  "rehber3bM3": "The system operates on a tight-layout assumption. In a single inspection +1 frame is normal, +2 frames is controlled expansion, and +3 or more is a cause for concern unless it is a super transition.",
  "rehber3bM4": "If feeder + 9 frames or feeder-free 10 frames reach 95% or more activation, the system reads this as the \"Add super\" threshold.",
  "rehber3bM5": "If feeder + 19 frames or feeder-free 20 frames reach 95% or more activation, the system generates an \"Add 3rd super\" alert.",
  "rehber3bM6": "A rapid frame drop coinciding with a harvest record is not counted as biological collapse; the system normalises this as harvest-induced volume contraction.",

  "rehber3cBaslik": "3C. Season Biology Matrix",
  "rehber3cM1": "İTOGENA does not read season as just a calendar name. For each season, brood expectation, stock pressure, pollen/bee bread expectation, queen purpose and activation coefficient are evaluated together.",
  "rehber3cM2": "The system treats winter, winter emergence, spring development, pre-honey flow, honey flow, post-harvest, autumn preparation and late autumn as separate biological behaviours.",
  "rehber3cM3": "This matrix does not give direct orders to the colony; it provides biological context for activation, capability, feeding, harvest and split decisions.",
  "rehber3cM4": "Season data is read together with local honey flow calibration. Therefore the same date may not mean the same decision at every apiary.",

  "rehber3dBaslik": "3D. Colony Trend and Normalised Momentum",
  "rehber3dM1": "Colony Trend describes not just today's strength but which direction the colony is heading. Momentum lives within this calculation.",
  "rehber3dM2": "Momentum is no longer a raw frame increase. A rapid post-harvest drop is not counted as biological collapse; a post-split drop is read as process-related; and adding a super is not counted as full growth until activation is complete, as it is a physical volume increase.",
  "rehber3dM3": "Super transition, risky rapid expansion, low activation and healthy upper-volume expansion within the honey flow are each normalised separately.",
  "rehber3dM4": "Colony Trend in the performance tab reads development direction, production direction, space pressure, recovery potential, collapse risk and normalised momentum together.",

  "rehber3eBaslik": "3E. Demography Projection",
  "rehber3eM1": "The demography projection does not perform an exact bee count; it estimates the workforce distribution within the colony from frame strength, brood load, season and development direction.",
  "rehber3eM2": "The system reads young worker, nurse bee, comb processor, house bee, guard, forager and drone distribution separately for field decisions.",
  "rehber3eM3": "Young worker capacity is used in raw comb and brood care decisions; forager capacity is used in honey flow and production decisions.",
  "rehber3eM4": "Demographic output is not an \"exact population\"; it is biological probability and a field projection.",

  "rehber3fBaslik": "3F. Workforce and Capability Projection",
  "rehber3fM1": "İTOGENA tries to interpret not just how many bees there are, but the biological capacity those bees have to perform specific tasks.",
  "rehber3fM2": "Comb drawing, brood care, nectar collection, honey processing, defence, recovery, winter hardiness and mating support are evaluated as separate workforce areas.",
  "rehber3fM3": "Two colonies with the same frame count can have different workforce capacities. Colonies with a low young-worker ratio may struggle with rapid comb processing or rearing brood even if they appear large.",
  "rehber3fM4": "This projection does not perform exact biological measurement; it produces an explainable biological trend model that supports field decisions.",

  "rehber3gBaslik": "3G. Risk Projection and Natural Risk Brakes",
  "rehber3gM1": "The risk projection does not manage the colony with alarming warnings; it produces a balanced decision brake by reading the season's natural risk premium and the colony's biological vulnerability together.",
  "rehber3gM2": "Varroa, bee-eater, hornet, robbing, moisture/winter, over-expansion, broodlessness/ageing and honey quality risks are all assessed in the same centre.",
  "rehber3gM3": "Risk brakes do not directly prohibit decisions. They make expansion, split, feeding, harvest and intervention suggestions more cautious through small coefficients.",
  "rehber3gM4": "This system does not make a definitive disease or pest diagnosis; it produces an explainable risk trend.",

  "rehber4Baslik": "4. Why Is Splitting Not Recommended Below 9 Frames?",
  "rehber4M1": "6 frames may be biologically possible; but it is not a safe field recommendation.",
  "rehber4M2": "İTOGENA gives not what is possible, but the right recommendation that protects the beekeeper from colony loss risk.",
  "rehber4M3": "The safe threshold for a split recommendation is 9 frames. The parent colony should be able to retain at least 5 frames after splitting, and the new split should be able to start with at least 4 frames.",
  "rehber4M4": "The 6–8 frame range is considered risky; rather than recommending a split, the system first advises strengthening.",
  "rehber4M5": "No split recommendation is made during the winter period.",
  "rehber4M6": "The split decision is read in time context. If there are more than 57 days until the honey flow, splitting a strong colony is meaningful; if fewer than 57 days remain, a standard split may reduce production strength.",

  "rehber5Baslik": "5. What Is the Difference Between Donor Score and General Score?",
  "rehber5M1": "General score is the colony's field performance.",
  "rehber5M2": "Donor score is the queen-rearing and genetic selection value.",
  "rehber5M3": "A general score of 85 alone does not mean donor eligibility. Swarm trace/genetic filter, lineage continuity, reproductive strength, hardiness and data confidence are also read.",
  "rehber5M4": "A strong colony caught by the genetic filter can be evaluated in production or closed-brood support; it is not placed in the queen-rearing pool.",

  "rehber6Baslik": "6. Swarm Trace and Post-Swarm Process",
  "rehber6M1": "Swarming is not a health problem; therefore it does not reduce the health score.",
  "rehber6M2": "A colony with swarm origin or swarm trace does not enter the donor pool.",
  "rehber6M3": "If marked as swarmed, the colony is not temporarily read as a production/harvest colony. The after-swarm risk is highest in days 0–7.",
  "rehber6M4": "After-swarm risk decreases in days 8–16. Days 17–30 are the new queen emergence, maturation and mating window.",
  "rehber6M5": "By days 31–45, laying should now be evident. If there is still no brood, the system evaluates this as queen failure or laying-worker risk.",

  "rehber7Baslik": "7. No-Brood Alarm and Decision Priority",
  "rehber7M1": "No brood is one of the most critical biological alarms. The system first checks whether this is a normal wait within an active split, post-swarm or queen-rearing window.",
  "rehber7M2": "If the waiting window has passed, no brood takes priority over routine decisions like varroa, feeding and harvest. On the grid card, colony continuity is discussed first.",
  "rehber7M3": "If laying-worker suspicion, drone brood pressure, consecutive broodless records and strength decline are seen together, the system treats this as a high-priority queen problem.",
  "rehber7M4": "If there is strong honey pressure within the honey flow, broodlessness is not immediately counted as queenlessness; space and honey pressure are evaluated first.",

  "rehber8Baslik": "8. How Is the Queen-Rearing Process Read?",
  "rehber8M1": "The queen-rearing process begins with triggers such as left queenless, split, sealed queen cell or a mated queen introduced.",
  "rehber8M2": "In a colony that will raise its own queen, sealed cells are destroyed on day 5; open/unsealed quality cells are left.",
  "rehber8M3": "In a colony where a mated queen has been introduced, the process is read according to acceptance and laying check.",
  "rehber8M4": "When daily or capped brood is seen, queen presence is indirectly accepted and the relevant queen-rearing process can close.",

  "rehber9Baslik": "9. What Is the 57/42-Day Honey Flow Logic?",
  "rehber9M1": "42 days is the biological period from egg to forager bee.",
  "rehber9M2": "57 days is the field planning threshold: approximately 15 days of safety margin is added to the 42-day biology.",
  "rehber9M3": "The decision engine takes split recommendations seriously according to this 57-day field window. If timing is not right, even a strong colony is not automatically made a split candidate.",
  "rehber9M4": "When 24 days or fewer remain to the honey flow, space, super, residue safety and swarm control come to the fore.",
  "rehber9M5": "The strongest decision window for queen replacement is the post-harvest / autumn entry period.",

  "rehber10Baslik": "10. How Do Varroa Alerts Work?",
  "rehber10M1": "Varroa alerts are read together with the season and honey flow window.",
  "rehber10M2": "Residue risk is taken into account before and during the honey flow.",
  "rehber10M3": "The post-harvest / late-summer early-autumn period is considered critical for the health of bees that will carry through winter.",
  "rehber10M4": "For oxalic, thymol, amitraz, formic and similar applications, the product label, licensed use instructions and local regulations must be followed.",

  "rehber11Baslik": "11. What Does Data Confidence Mean?",
  "rehber11M1": "With a single-inspection colony, the system makes a decision but states that data confidence is low.",
  "rehber11M2": "2–4 inspections is the monitoring band. 5 or more inspections is the start of reliable evaluation.",
  "rehber11M3": "Data confidence is shown to explain why a decision is strong or limited; it is not meant to leave the user undecided.",

  "rehber12Baslik": "12. What Is the Biological Model and Capability Analysis?",
  "rehber12M1": "İTOGENA does not read frame count just as a number; it interprets the estimated brood-box layout, brood block, stock area and harvest-candidate outer frames from standard colony organisation.",
  "rehber12M2": "Hive type can be selected as Langstroth or Dadant. If a feeder is present, the lower brood box is 9 frames; without a feeder, 10 frames.",
  "rehber12M3": "Using temporal polyethism logic, the age-related task distribution of worker bees is estimated: nurse bee, comb builder, house bee, forager and drone density are used as capability scores.",
  "rehber12M4": "When the system says \"harvest these frames\" it does not make a definitive judgement; it only points to outer/super frames that, based on the estimated layout, could be considered for harvest if they are brood-free and capped.",

  "rehber13Baslik": "13. How Does Winter Management Work?",
  "rehber13M1": "In winter the primary goal is survival, not production. The system prioritises external observation, weight feel and moisture/water entry check in a way that prevents unnecessary hive opening.",
  "rehber13M2": "If stock appears very low, starvation risk takes higher priority than the minimum-intervention rule.",
  "rehber13M3": "If physical volume is high but functional bee strength is low, the system flags the risk of empty volume and heat loss.",

  "rehber14Baslik": "14. How Is Genetic Multiplication Value Read?",
  "rehber14M1": "Genetic multiplication value is not just honey or frame count. Functional capacity, brood layout, development direction, activation, risk, stock/winter safety and swarm trace are all read together.",
  "rehber14M2": "Colonies with swarm origin or swarm trace may be valuable in production; but they are not automatically highlighted as clean genetic propagation candidates.",
  "rehber14M3": "This score is not a definitive breeding verdict; it is a strategic signal that supports monitoring colonies worth multiplying and making controlled split decisions at the right time.",

  "rehber15Baslik": "15. What Does Economic Value Represent?",
  "rehber15M1": "The economic value screen is not a precise income calculation, but an approximate apiary asset and estimated honey potential projection.",
  "rehber15M2": "Active hive count, total framed bees, empty hives, drawn combs and estimated harvestable honey potential are all read together.",
  "rehber15M3": "The user enters the honey kg sale price; the system multiplies the estimated harvest potential by this price and produces a potential value band.",
  "rehber15M4": "Honey yield varies depending on flora, weather, harvest timing, remaining stock and the beekeeper's management.",

  "rehber16Baslik": "16. How Does the Feeding Decision Projection Work?",
  "rehber16M1": "Feeding suggestions are not precise stock measurements; frame strength, brood area, season, active process, honey flow window and the user's inspection observation are evaluated together.",
  "rehber16M2": "The system does not give a precise prescription; it produces an estimated ml/L or gram band.",
  "rehber16M3": "1:1 syrup is mostly for development support; 2:1 syrup for stock replenishment; pollen supplement is considered meaningful only if pollen pressure is confirmed in the field.",
  "rehber16M4": "If 20 days or fewer remain to the honey flow and the colony is targeting harvest, sugar-based feeding is not recommended.",

  "rehber17Baslik": "17. İTOGENA Decision Glossary",
  "rehber17Kutu": "This section explains what the terms seen on screen mean.",
  "rehber17M1": "Colony Trend: Describes not just today's strength, but which direction the colony is progressing.",
  "rehber17M2": "Colony Strength: Reflects the live bee and frame strength at the last inspection.",
  "rehber17M3": "Colony Health: The combined reading of brood layout, queen process, broodlessness, varroa period, behaviour and risk signals.",
  "rehber17M4": "Functional Frame: Not the physical frame count in the hive, but the biological capacity the bees are actually using.",
  "rehber17M5": "Volume Activation: Describes how much of a given frame or super the colony has made usable.",
  "rehber17M6": "Normalised Momentum: Does not read short-term frame increase or decrease in raw form. Post-harvest drop, split, super transition and risky rapid expansion are separated.",
  "rehber17M7": "Genetic Filter: The colony may be valuable in production yet is not placed in the queen-rearing pool.",
  "rehber17M8": "Management Decision: The actions the beekeeper will take in the field, such as feeding, super, space, post-harvest care, varroa and winter preparation.",
  "rehber17M9": "Process: A time-bound biological/management window such as queen rearing, post-split recovery, post-swarm or no-brood diagnosis.",
  "rehber17M10": "Lock / Wait: Describes a sensitive window where intervention should not occur.",
  "rehber17M11": "Data Confidence: Describes how many inspections the decision is based on.",

  "rehber18Baslik": "18. On Which Topics Does the App Not Give a Definitive Verdict?",
  "rehber18U1": "İTOGENA is not a substitute for veterinary advice, licensed medication use or official regulations.",
  "rehber18U2": "For chemical treatments, the product label, licensed use instructions, protective equipment and local regulations must be followed.",
  "rehber18U3": "Weather, flora, local nectar flow, beekeeper experience and colony behaviour must be observed separately in the field.",
  "rehber18U4": "The system supports the right decision; final responsibility lies with the beekeeper in the field.",

  "rehber19Baslik": "19. Voice Note",
  "rehber19M1": "You can add a voice note by pressing the microphone icon in the notes field and speaking.",
  "rehber19M2": "Your speech is automatically converted to text and added to the notes field.",
  "rehber19U1": "Wind, bee noise, the device microphone and internet connection on some devices may affect recognition.",

